Automated test-driven development makes your code:

  • easier and faster to write
  • less prone to bugs
  • easier to amend
  • easier to review

What is a test

Tests are bundles of code that check for expected behaviour. It is not about HOW your code is going to solve your problem, but WHAT a solution is going to look like. The core of a test is an expectation

  • A test is code that tests the behaviour of your code
  • They are about testing WHAT your code does, not HOW

What is a test

Here is an example expectation using the testthat package It contains an object that you are testing

expect_equal (
  object = 1 + 1, # This is a function call - `+`(1, 1)
  expected = 2
  )

What is a test

and some expectation regarding it's behaviour

expect_equal (
  object = 1 + 1,
  expected = 2
  )

What to test

What to test

There is a fine balance between what (and how many) tests you should write.

A short simple piece of code should not have a lot of tests

… but if you don't have enough tests, you could miss problems

What to test

What to test

General output behaviour

  • a number + a number outputs a number
  • what happens if we pass a character?
  • … a vector of numbers?
  • … an empty vector?
  • …NA?
  • … a numeric vector with an NA in?

What to test

Specific output behaviour:

  • 1 + 1 = 2

  • 1 + 0 = 1

  • 1 + (-1) = 0

  • c(1, 2, 3) + 1 = c(2, 3, 4)

  • c(1, 2, 3) + c(1, 2, 3) = c(2, 4, 6)

  • a + b > a for b > 0

  • a + b < a for b < 0

Some jargon

Unit testing is about writing tests for the smallest testable component of your code. If you are using R, this is about testing functions.

Googling testing brings up a whole lot of other impenetrable jargon but of note are Component testing and System testing.

  • A unit is the smallest testable component of code (in R, probably a function)
  • Integration testing tests how units work together
  • System testing tests the integration of all units

Test-driven development

THIS IS THE MOST IMPORTANT BIT

I would imagine that an awful lot of you, when faced with a coding problem, do your coding first and then sense check that it works through little code snippets to make sure nothing untoward is going on.

The good news is that you are already testing!

However are you running those snippets every time you work on your code? Maybe you've broken something essential without realising.

Switching to a test-driven workflow will help you in producing robust code first time

Test-driven development

The first step in coding your solution is to sit down and think about what you expect your code to do.

Benefits

  • robust planning of code behaviour

  • harder to fix a bug and inadvertantly create a new one without noticing

  • faster checking of completed code

  • reviewed code can be refactored without having to be re-reviewed

  • users can be confident code is working correctly

Drawbacks

Drawbacks

  • Writing too many unnecessary tests is a drain on your time

  • Poorly thought-out tests can lead to overestimates of robustness

Writing automated tests in R

  • The testthat package

  • Contains functions that help you write tests

  • Contains functions that let you automate testing on scripts, directories and packages
